{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b04b2975-3e5f-41fe-9f99-e82887eb67bb","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, the OS automatically generates a **crash report**. Look here:\n\n1. **User-level reports:**\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **System-level reports:**\n   ```\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\nFiles are named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS). Open them with any text editor — they contain the stack trace, exception type, and register state.\n\nYou can also use **Console.app** → sidebar → *Crash Reports* to browse them with a GUI.\n\n**To get a core dump** instead (for use with `lldb`):\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n/cores/    # core dumps land here (e.g., /cores/core.<pid>)\n```\n\nThen debug with:\n```bash\nlldb ./YourApp -c /cores/core.<pid>\n```\n\n> **Note:** Core dumps may be disabled by SIP on modern macOS. The `.ips` crash reports are usually the most reliable source.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"de227aa9-3972-4d9a-bc46-84493e991c18","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET application on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no codebase exploration needed.","outputTokens":335},"id":"9488f453-12f5-489f-955f-16d6c77c8815","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:54:34.851Z","parentId":"5b0c40d2-e891-40c2-8f50-f30cf2ed0bea"}
